Neural Networks for Bank Churn Prediction¶

Businesses like banks that provide service have to worry about the problem of 'Churn' i.e. customers leaving and joining another service provider. It is important to understand which aspects of the service influence a customer's decision in this regard. Management can concentrate efforts on the improvement of service, keeping in mind these priorities.

The case study is from an open-source dataset from Kaggle. The dataset contains 10,000 sample points with 14 distinct features such as CustomerId, CreditScore, Geography, Gender, Age, Tenure, Balance, etc. Link to the Kaggle project site:https://www.kaggle.com/barelydedicated/bank-customer-churn-modeling

RowNumber: Row number.
CustomerId: Unique identification key for different customers.
Surname: Surname of the customer
Credit Score: Credit score is a measure of an individual's ability to pay back the borrowed amount. It is the numerical representation of their creditworthiness. A credit score is a 3-digit number that falls in the range of 300-900, 900 being the highest.
Geography: The country to which the customer belongs.
Gender: The gender of the customer.
Age: Age of the customer.
Tenure: The period of time a customer has been associated with the bank.
Balance: The account balance (the amount of money deposited in the bank account) of the customer.
NumOfProducts: How many accounts, bank account affiliated products the person has.
HasCrCard: Does the customer have a credit card through the bank?
IsActiveMember: Subjective, but for the concept
EstimatedSalary: Estimated salary of the customer.
Exited: Did they leave the bank after all?

#I first try a learning rate of 0.01, batch size of 10, and relu activations
model = Sequential()
model.add(Dense(13,activation='relu'))
model.add(Dense(10, activation ='relu'))
model.add(Dense(5, activation ='relu'))
model.add(Dense(2,activation='softmax'))
optimizer = keras.optimizers.RMSprop(lr=0.01)
model.compile(loss='categorical_crossentropy',optimizer=optimizer,metrics=['accuracy'])
history = model.fit(X_train, y_train, epochs= 50, validation_split = 0.2, batch_size = 10, verbose = True)
hist  = pd.DataFrame(history.history)
hist['epoch'] = history.epoch

In [24]:
def GetCM(y_pred, results):
    predictions = []
    for pred in y_pred:
        predictions.append(np.argmax(pred))
    conf_mat = metrics.confusion_matrix(y_test, results['Predicted'].values)
    cr=metrics.classification_report(y_test, results['Predicted'].values)
    print(cr)
    print(conf_mat)

In [28]:
lr = [0.01, 0.001, 0.0001]
for i in lr:
    model = Sequential()
    model.add(Dense(13,activation='relu'))
    model.add(Dense(10, activation ='relu'))
    model.add(Dense(5, activation ='relu'))
    model.add(Dense(2,activation='softmax'))
    optimizer = keras.optimizers.RMSprop(lr=i)
    model.compile(loss='categorical_crossentropy',optimizer=optimizer, metrics=['accuracy'])
    history = model.fit(X_train, y_train, epochs= 50, validation_split = 0.2, batch_size = 10, verbose = False)
    hist  = pd.DataFrame(history.history)
    hist['epoch'] = history.epoch
    plt.plot(hist['loss'])
    plt.plot(hist['val_loss'])
    plt.legend(("train", "valid") , loc =0)
    plt.show()
    results = pd.DataFrame()
    results['Actual'] = y_test.values
    y_pred = model.predict(X_test)
    predictions = []
    for pred in y_pred:
        predictions.append(np.argmax(pred))
    results['Probability that output is 0'] = model.predict_proba(X_test)[:,0]
    results['Probability that output is 1'] = model.predict_proba(X_test)[:,1]
    results['Predicted'] = predictions 
    #Sklearn has threshold of 0.5 but here I explicitly set it to 0.5 to be thorough
    results['Predicted'] = results['Probability that output is 1'].map(lambda x: 1 if x > 0.5 else 0)
    GetCM(y_pred, results)
    loss, accuracy = model.evaluate(X_test, caty_test, verbose = 0)
    print('Accuracy: %.3f'  % accuracy)
    print('Loss: %.3f' % loss)

Insights: The convergence is a lot smoother in the 0.0001 learning rate trial, this seems to be a good value for this model. The loss for the validation set is mostly steadily decreasing, which is an improvement from the previous trials. From higher learning rates, I note that the validation loss does not decrease along with the training set, which is undesirable.
The accuracy for the 0.0001 learning rate model is pretty much the same as the other trials. However, I got the best convergence using this learning rate and will proceed with this

#Now, I will tune the batch size parameter
batches = [5, 10, 30, 50, 100]
for i in batches:
    model = Sequential()
    model.add(Dense(13,activation='relu'))
    model.add(Dense(10, activation ='relu'))
    model.add(Dense(5, activation ='relu'))
    model.add(Dense(2,activation='softmax'))
    optimizer = keras.optimizers.RMSprop(lr=0.0001)
    model.compile(loss='categorical_crossentropy',optimizer=optimizer, metrics=['accuracy'])
    history = model.fit(X_train, y_train, epochs= 50, validation_split = 0.2, batch_size = i, verbose = False)
    hist  = pd.DataFrame(history.history)
    hist['epoch'] = history.epoch
    plt.plot(hist['loss'])
    plt.plot(hist['val_loss'])
    plt.legend(("train", "valid") , loc =0)
    plt.show()
    results = pd.DataFrame()
    results['Actual'] = y_test.values
    y_pred = model.predict(X_test)
    predictions = []
    for pred in y_pred:
        predictions.append(np.argmax(pred))
    results['Probability that output is 0'] = model.predict_proba(X_test)[:,0]
    results['Probability that output is 1'] = model.predict_proba(X_test)[:,1]
    results['Predicted'] = predictions 
    #Sklearn has threshold of 0.5 but here I explicitly set it to 0.5 to be thorough
    results['Predicted'] = results['Probability that output is 1'].map(lambda x: 1 if x > 0.5 else 0)
    GetCM(y_pred, results)
    loss, accuracy = model.evaluate(X_test, caty_test, verbose = 0)
    print('Accuracy: %.3f'  % accuracy)
    print('Loss: %.3f' % loss)

def loss_test(loss):
    model = Sequential()
    model.add(Dense(13,activation='relu'))
    model.add(Dense(10, activation ='relu'))
    model.add(Dense(5, activation ='relu'))
    model.add(Dense(2,activation='softmax'))
    optimizer = keras.optimizers.RMSprop(lr=0.0001)
    model.compile(loss=loss,optimizer=optimizer, metrics=['accuracy'])
    history = model.fit(X_train, y_train, epochs= 50, validation_split = 0.2, batch_size = 5, verbose = False)
    hist  = pd.DataFrame(history.history)
    hist['epoch'] = history.epoch
    plt.plot(hist['loss'])
    plt.plot(hist['val_loss'])
    plt.legend(("train", "valid") , loc =0)
    plt.show()
    results = pd.DataFrame()
    results['Actual'] = y_test.values
    y_pred = model.predict(X_test)
    predictions = []
    for pred in y_pred:
        predictions.append(np.argmax(pred))
    results['Probaility that output is 0'] = model.predict_proba(X_test)[:,0]
    results['Probability that output is 1'] = model.predict_proba(X_test)[:,1]
    results['Predicted'] = predictions 
    #Sklearn has threshold of 0.5 but here I explicitly set it to 0.5 to be thorough
    results['Predicted'] = results['Probability that output is 1'].map(lambda x: 1 if x > 0.5 else 0)
    GetCM(y_pred, results)
    loss, accuracy = model.evaluate(X_test, caty_test, verbose = 0)
    print('Accuracy: %.3f'  % accuracy)
    print('Loss: %.3f' % loss)

Insights: Overall, it seems that our tuned model is performing decently, with around a 85.6% accuracy. From our metrics, we can see that the model predicts non-exiting individuals far better. This is because most of the observations in our dataset are non-exiting customers and is training more on those observations. The recall value for predicting exiting customers is only 36%, which is not very good. For our model to work more effectively, it is necessary to obtain larger dataframes with more information about exiting customers. This will allow the model to train on this information more and in turn yield higher classification accuracy and recall overall. Despite this, our tuned model is performing successfully as it reaches convergence (based on the plot) and predicts customer behavior somewhat well.
